            <div class="planet-card">
                <h3>PSR B1257+12 b (Draugr)</h3>
                <p>
                    PSR B1257+12 b, alternatively designated PSR B1257+12 A and named Draugr, is an extrasolar planet located approximately 2,300 light-years (710 pc) away in the constellation of Virgo. 
                    It orbits the pulsar Lich, making it part of a dead stellar system. Draugr is about twice as massive as the Moon and is currently the least massive known planet with an accurately determined mass.
                </p>
                
                <h4>Discovery</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Discovered by:</strong> Aleksander Wolszczan, Maciej Konacki</li>
                    <li><strong>Discovery site:</strong> United States</li>
                    <li><strong>Discovery date:</strong> April 22, 1994</li>
                    <li><strong>Detection method:</strong> Pulsar Timing</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h4>Orbital Characteristics</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Semi-major axis:</strong> 0.19 AU (28,000,000 km)</li>
                    <li><strong>Eccentricity:</strong> 0.0</li>
                    <li><strong>Orbital period:</strong> 25.262 ± 0.003 days</li>
                    <li><strong>Inclination:</strong> 50° (assumed)</li>
                    <li><strong>Time of periastron:</strong> 2,449,765.6 ± 0.2</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h4>Physical Characteristics</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Mass:</strong> 0.020 ± 0.002 ME</li>
                    <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> 266 K (−7 °C; 19 °F)</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="photo-container">
                    <div class="photo">
                <img src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/psr-b1257-12b.jpg?w=768&format=webp" 
                    alt="Draugr" class="exoplanet-img">
                    <a href="https://eyes.nasa.gov/apps/exo/?destinations=/alien-worlds/strange-new-worlds/#/planet/PSR_B1257+12_b"
                    target="_blank">Learn more</a>
                </div>
                </div>
            

            <div class="planet-card">
                <h3>TRAPPIST-1 d</h3>
                <p>
                    TRAPPIST-1 d is a small exoplanet, with about 40% of Earth's mass, located on the inner edge of the habitable zone of the ultracool dwarf star TRAPPIST-1. This star is situated 40.7 light-years (12.5 parsecs) away from Earth in the constellation of Aquarius. 
                    The planet was discovered using the transit method, with its first signs appearing in 2016. Further details about the planet's characteristics emerged in the following years.
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    TRAPPIST-1 d is the second-least massive planet in its system and likely has a compact, hydrogen-poor atmosphere, similar to Venus, Earth, or Mars. Receiving only 4.3% more sunlight than Earth, it is located on the inner edge of the habitable zone. The planet likely has a volatile layer, possibly consisting of atmosphere, oceans, and ice. However, a 2018 study from the University of Washington suggested that it might have a Venus-like, uninhabitable atmosphere.
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    TRAPPIST-1 d is also considered an eyeball planet candidate, with a narrow band of water between its hot day side and icy night side, as illustrated below.
                </p>
                
                <h4>Planetary Characteristics</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Planet Type:</strong> Terrestrial</li>
                    <li><strong>Planet Radius:</strong> 0.788 × Earth</li>
                    <li><strong>Planet Mass:</strong> 0.388 × Earth</li>
                    <li><strong>Orbital Radius:</strong> 0.02227 AU</li>
                    <li><strong>Orbital Period:</strong> 4 days</li>
                    <li><strong>Eccentricity:</strong> 0.01</li>
                    <li><strong>Discovery Method:</strong> Transit</li>
                    <li><strong>Discovery Date:</strong> 2016</li>
                </ul>
                
                <div class="photo-container">
                    <div class="photo">
                <img src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/trappist-1-jpg.webp?w=768&format=webp"
