            <div class="planet-card">
                <h3>GJ 273 b</h3>
                <p>
                    GJ 273 b is a super-Earth exoplanet that orbits an M-type star. It has a mass of 2.89 Earths and takes 18.6 days to complete one orbit around its star, located 0.091101 AU away. The discovery of GJ 273 b was announced in 2017, and it was detected using the radial velocity method.
                </p>
                
                <h4>Planetary Characteristics</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Planet Type:</strong> Super Earth</li>
                    <li><strong>Planet Radius:</strong> 1.51 × Earth (estimate)</li>
                    <li><strong>Planet Mass:</strong> 2.89 × Earth</li>
                    <li><strong>Orbital Radius:</strong> 0.091101 AU</li>
                    <li><strong>Orbital Period:</strong> 18.6 days</li>
                    <li><strong>Eccentricity:</strong> 0.1</li>
                    <li><strong>Discovery Method:</strong> Radial Velocity</li>
                    <li><strong>Discovery Date:</strong> 2017</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="photo-container"></div>
                    <div class="photo">
                    <img src="https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/stsci-01gysy4shv3hdb6v912zbsgs46.jpg" 
                    alt="GJ 273 b" 
                    class="exoplanet-img">
                </div>
                </div>
                
            

                <div class="planet-card">
                    <h3>51 Pegasi b (Dimidium)</h3>
                    <p>
                        51 Pegasi b, officially named Dimidium (/dɪˈmɪdiəm/), is an extrasolar planet located approximately 50 light-years (15 parsecs) away in the constellation Pegasus. It was the first exoplanet discovered orbiting a main-sequence star, the Sun-like 51 Pegasi, marking a major breakthrough in astronomy. Dimidium is the prototype for a class of planets known as hot Jupiters.
                    </p>
                    
                    <h4>Discovery</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Discovered by:</strong> Michel Mayor and Didier Queloz</li>
                        <li><strong>Discovery site:</strong> OHP, France</li>
                        <li><strong>Discovery date:</strong> 6 October 1995</li>
                        <li><strong>Detection method:</strong> Radial Velocity (ELODIE)</li>
                    </ul>
                
                    <h4>Orbital Characteristics</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Aphelion:</strong> 0.0534 AU (7,990,000 km)</li>
                        <li><strong>Perihelion:</strong> 0.0520 AU (7,780,000 km)</li>
                        <li><strong>Semi-major axis:</strong> 0.0527 ± 0.0030 AU (7,880,000 ± 450,000 km)</li>
                        <li><strong>Eccentricity:</strong> 0.013 ± 0.012</li>
                        <li><strong>Orbital period:</strong> 4.230785 ± 0.000036 days (101.5388 hours)</li>
                        <li><strong>Average orbital speed:</strong> 136 km/s</li>
                    </ul>
                
                    <h4>Physical Characteristics</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Mean radius:</strong> 1.9 ± 0.3 RJ</li>
                        <li><strong>Mass:</strong> ≥ 0.472 ± 0.039 MJ</li>
                        <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> 1284 ± 19 K</li>
                        <li><strong>Atmospheric composition:</strong> Traces of water were discovered in 2017.</li>
                    </ul>
                
                    <p>
                        In 2019, the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded, in part, for the discovery of 51 Pegasi b.
                    </p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="photo-container">
                    <div class="photo">
                    <img src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/2_planet_profile_51_pegasi_b_3_2.jpg?w=768&format=webp" 
                    alt="Artist's impression of 51 Pegasi b" 
                    class="exoplanet-img">
                </div>
            </div>
           
                

                     

                    <div class="planet-card">
                        <h3>Proxima Centauri b</h3>
                        <p>
                            At only four light-years away, Proxima Centauri b is our closest known exoplanet neighbor. It is classified as a super-Earth exoplanet that orbits an M-type star, Proxima Centauri.
                        </p>
                        
                        <h4>Key Characteristics</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Mass:</strong> 1.27 Earths</li>
                            <li><strong>Orbital Period:</strong> 11.2 days</li>
                            <li><strong>Distance from Star:</strong> 0.0485 AU</li>
                            <li><strong>Discovery Date:</strong> 2016</li>
                        </ul>
                    
                        <h4>Habitable Zone and Radiation</h4>
                        <p>
                            Proxima b lies in the habitable zone of its star, where conditions could allow for liquid water to exist. However, it encounters bouts of extreme ultraviolet radiation that are hundreds of times greater than what Earth receives from the Sun. This radiation generates enough energy to strip away not only the lightest molecules, like hydrogen, but also heavier elements such as oxygen and nitrogen over time.
                        </p>
                    
                        <h4>Considerations for Habitability</h4>
                        <p>
                            While Proxima b’s orbit is in the habitable zone, several factors affect its potential for habitability:
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>The actual presence of water on the planet.</li>
                            <li>Whether an atmosphere can survive at its orbit.</li>
                            <li>Atmospheres are essential for life as we know it, allowing for climate regulation, maintaining surface pressure suitable for liquid water, shielding from hazardous space weather, and supporting the chemical building blocks of life.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <div class="photo-container">
                            <div class="photo">
                        <img src="https://science.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/potw1343a-jpg.webp?w=768&format=webp"
                         alt="Proxima Centauri b"
                          class="exoplanet-img">
                            </div>
                    </div>

